3️⃣ Explanation of YOUR APIs
🔹 1st API – Save Student
@PostMapping("/save")
private Student createStudent(@RequestBody Student student){
    return service.saveStudent(student);
}


✔ @PostMapping → create/save data
✔ @RequestBody → JSON → Java object
✔ Data saved in DB

🔹 2nd API – Get All Students
@GetMapping("/all")
public List<Student> getAllStudents(){
    return service.getAllStudentData();
}


✔ @GetMapping → read data
✔ Returns list of students
✔ Automatically converted to JSON

🔹 3rd API – Get Student by ID (RequestParam)
@GetMapping
public Student getStudentById(@RequestParam Integer id) {
    return service.getStudentById(id);
}


URL:

GET /api/std?id=5


✔ @RequestParam → reads query parameter
✔ Used for filtering/searching

🔹 4th API – Update Student
@PutMapping("/{id}")
public Student updateStudent(@PathVariable Integer id,@RequestBody Student student) {
    return service.updateStudent(id, student);
}


✔ @PutMapping → update existing data
✔ @PathVariable → reads value from URL
✔ @RequestBody → updated data from client

4️⃣ ALL annotations used (IMPORTANT)
🔸 @RestController

Marks class as REST controller
Returns JSON, not view

🔸 @RequestMapping("api/std")
Base URL for all APIs

/api/std/save
/api/std/all

🔸 @Autowired
Injects dependency automatically
Used for Service / Repository

🔸 @PostMapping
Handles POST HTTP requests
Used to create/save data

🔸 @GetMapping
Handles GET HTTP requests
Used to read/fetch data

🔸 @PutMapping
Handles PUT HTTP requests
Used to update data

🔸 @RequestBody
Converts JSON → Java object
Uses Jackson internally

🔸 @PathVariable
Reads value from URL path
Example:

/api/std/10

🔸 @RequestParam
Reads value from query string
Example:
/api/std?id=10

5️⃣ Interview-ready one-liner ⭐
In Spring Boot, @PostMapping is used to accept data from the client and save it on the server, while @GetMapping is used to read data from the server and return it to the client.

